        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The target HDO line is weak, and we choose the lowest angular resolution of 1.6" achievable in band 8 after smoothing to maximize the signal strength. The emission, extending over ~120 AU=2.3" will be marginally resolved by the observations, allowing us to test the radial distribution (in addition to the information we will get from the resolved line profile).
The required sensitivity of 5.1 mK is based on our goal to detect at &gt;3 sigma the expected peak signal of 20 mJy in 0.2 km/s channels, and higher S/N on the integrated emission. The line-to-continuum ratio is &lt;220 and reachable with standard calibration.
We place 4 windows in 2 basebands to record the HDO 101-000 line, the N2H+ 5-4 line (which will be detected as high S/N), the N2D+ 6-5 line (which we expect to be detected), and two NH2D 202-111 lines, which may be detected given the positive detection of NH3 with Herschel.
Each window contains enough line-free regions for continuum subtraction. Furthermore, two basebands are used to record the 4 GHz continuum over the entire band, where we will obtain very high S/N.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
